04518nam a22006015i 9780226365312DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017030478  a9780226365312  a(DE-B1597)524402  a(OCoLC)1024191227  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aB53b.H32413 2017 4aB53 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a101223  aCC 11002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/17603:1 aHampe, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Philosophy Is For /cMichael Hampe. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the American Edition -- tONE. Asserting, Narrating, Educating -- tTWO. Maieutic and Academic Philosophy -- tTHREE. Life, Subjectivity, Assimilation -- tFOUR. The Life of Assertive Beings, Linguistic Dissidence -- tFIVE. Ordinary Language, Theories, and Explanations -- tSIX. The Ordinary and Its Truth -- tSEVEN. Expertocracy and the Education of Individuals -- tEIGHT. Freedom, Necessity, Creativity -- tNINE. Reacting to the World -- tTEN. Telling Stories about Assertions and Arguments -- tELEVEN. Concreteness and Critique -- tTWELVE. Arriving at the End of Asserting -- tEpilogue to the History of Philosophy -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex of Personal Names0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is the state of philosophy today, and what might it be tomorrow? With What Philosophy Is For, Michael Hampe answers these questions by exploring the relationships among philosophy, education, science, and narrative, developing a Socratic critique of philosophical doctrines. Philosophers generally develop systematic theories that lay out the basic structures of human experience, in order to teach the rest of humanity how to rightly understand our place in the world. This “scientific” approach to philosophy, Hampe argues, is too one-sided. In this magnum opus of an essay, Hampe aims to rescue philosophy from its current narrow claims of doctrine and to remind us what it is really for—to productively disillusion us into clearer thinking. Hampe takes us through twenty-five hundred years of intellectual history, starting with Socrates. That archetype of the philosophical teacher did not develop strict doctrines and rules, but rather criticized and refuted doctrines. With the Socratic method, we see the power of narration at work. Narrative and analytical disillusionment, Hampe argues, are the most helpful long-term enterprises of thought, the ones most worth preserving and developing again. What Philosophy Is For is simultaneously an introduction, a critique, and a call to action. Hampe shows how and why philosophy became what it is today, and, crucially, shows what it could be once more, if it would only turn its back on its pretensions to dogma: a privileged space for reflecting on the human condition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPhilosophyxStudy and teaching. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aSocratic method.  acritique.  ahuman condition.  aphilosophy.1 aWinkler, Michael.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022636528240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226365312423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226365312/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles